title: Birds seen at 145 Gibsons Road, Cobains
description: Birds that have been photographed or seen at 145 Gibsons Road, Cobains.  This is a 6 acre property with a growing garden of predominantly Australian native plants.  Much of the boundary plantings are of indigenous vegetation.

items.title: Anthochaera chrysoptera
items.content_text: This is the first time I have seen Brush Wattlebirds here, but we have had Red Wattlebirds here for years.

items.title: Petroica boodang
items.content_text: This Scarlet Robin appears to have a broken beak.  Hope it will be able to feed all right.

items.title: Haliastur sphenurus
items.content_text: This is possibly the same bird as in my previous post, but photos taken a different day - same dead rabbit!

items.title: Rhipidura rufifrons
items.content_text: So pleased to see this Rufous Fantail flipping around this morning.  I have never seen one before.

items.title: Accipiter fasciatus
items.content_text: Raptor bathing in one of our birdbaths.

items.title: Rhipidura albiscapa
items.content_text: Bird, with three babies (can be seen) in nest.

items.title: Anas superciliosa
items.content_text: Two Pacific Black ducks were in the backyard for a while.  Guess they were checking out nesting spots.

items.title: Neochmia temporalis
items.content_text: Lots of Red-browed firetails feeding in the grass.

items.title: Coturnix ypsilophora
items.content_text: This quail has been spotted a few times lately, moving between bushes and hiding, but today I managed to get these couple of terrible photos.  Both my husband and I thought it looked more like a Brown Quail than a Stubble Quail.

items.title: Circus assimilis
items.content_text: Spotted Harrier eating a rabbit.

items.title: Acanthiza pusilla
items.content_text: Bird found sitting on the window sill in the shed.  Brown Thornbill??

items.title: Accipiter cirrhocephalus
items.content_text: The bird returned!  Guess it is the same one.  First saw it sitting in the Allocasuarina next to the bird bath, resting on one leg.  It flew down to the bird bath, drank, then bathed in the water.  When I walked outside, it flew up to one of the big eucalypts nearby.  These photos show it to have a rounded tail (definitely not squared), so still wonder if it is a Brown Goshawk.  Although the last photo does show it to have a longer middle toe, other photos don't seem to show such a difference.  I am just confused about Identification of this bird - if it is the same one as I photographed the other day in the birdbath!

items.title: Accipiter cirrhocephalus
items.content_text: This big bird was sitting in our birdbath.  It has been identified by Albert Golden as a Collared Sparrowhawk.  He commented that the long middle toe and 'goggle' eyes identified it as such.  It would have been sitting (as in the first photo) for at least 5 minutes while we were watching.  It did look at me standing in the doorway with the camera, but appeared unperturbed.  It then flew to a nearby tree (scattering little birds in all directions), then flew back to the birdbath, where it sat on the lip for another 5 minutes or thereabouts before flying away.

items.title: Haliastur sphenurus
items.content_text: This was a very large bird.  When first seen, it was swooping low over the grass, then sat on the back fence post while I fetched the camera.

items.title: Microeca fascinans
items.content_text: Little bird that perched on the wire and would periodically fly to catch insects, then land back on the wire again.  I wondered if it is a Jacky Winter?

items.title: Neochmia temporalis
items.content_text: This bird is sitting on the doormat after it crashed into the glass door.  It flew away shortly after this photo was taken.

items.title: Pachycephala spp.
items.content_text: Smaller than a Grey Shrike thrush and with pale yellow on the wings.

items.title: Pachycephala rufiventris
items.content_text: Singing a beautiful song.  Smallish bird.

items.title: Aquila audax
items.content_text: Very large bird.  Photo taken from considerable distance.

items.title: Sericornis frontalis
items.content_text: Small bird. Pale yellowish breast. Brown and chestnut brown on back. White eyes.

items.title: Ardea modesta
items.content_text: ID corrected by Andrew Allen (29/10/17). Kink in neck and gape extending behind the eye makes it a Great Egret. Also large size. Often confused with Intermediate Egret which doesn't have these features.
